ess key aspects of this long film history, marked by such towering figures as Jean Renoir, Jacques Tati and Jean-Luc Godard. Idyllic or menacing, expansive or claustrophobic, the suburb served divergent aesthetic and ideological programmes across the better part of a century. Themes central to French cultural modernity – class conflict, leisure, boredom and anti-authoritarianism – cut across the fifteen chapters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion pictureszFrancexHistory. 0aSuburbs in motion pictures. 0aSuburbszFrance. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2019. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aFrench filmmaking.  aarchitecture.  afilm genres.  ahousing projects.  amodernisation.  anew towns.  asocial class.  asuburbs and suburbanisation.1 aBullot, Erik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanteux, Camille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCardonne-Arlyck, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaucon, Térésa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlinn, Margaret C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFourcaut, Annie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJean, Tristan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLack, Roland-François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMet, Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMet, Philippe, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPautrot, Jean-Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReader, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchilling, Derek, 